passages.text: USA | Automotive Aftermarket
August Monthly Tune- Up

Our Tune- Up is a monthly look at key Aftermarket metrics. The latest available government driving data (June) was \(+0.9\%\) y/y (285.6B mi), and TTM VMT \(+1.0\%\) y/y. Our VMT model estimates that July \((+0.1\%\) y/y) saw a slight y/y increase in vehicle utilization. Meanwhile, through July, the Aftermarket Index has outperformed the S&P 500 in \(^{2}5\) , posting a \(+12.2\%\) increase vs \(+7.8\%\) .

Update of our predictive VMT model for July. We update our predictive VMT model, projecting July driving volumes well ahead of available government data (June most recent). We note that throughout its history, our prediction model shows a correlation of predicted miles driven vs reported miles driven of \(\sim 88\%\) , with an average prediction error of \(\sim 2.8\%\) . Our model prediction for July VMT is 291.2B miles \((+0.1\%\) y/y), with an upper limit of 304.3B miles and a lower limit of 277.1B miles.

Our Scrap Price Index, which is an average aggregate of five zones from American Recycler News, was \(- 8.4\%\) y/y to 204 in August, \(- 0.8\%\) from the prior month. In July, the Manheim Index was \(+2.9\%\) y/y to 207.4, \(- 0.5\%\) vs the prior month, and the Black Book Index was \(+1.0\%\) y/y to 146.5.

On a yr/yr basis, the US\$ was weaker against the CAD \((- 0.1\%)\) , the EUR \((- 7.1\%)\) and the GBP \((- 4.7\%)\) . Compared with the prior month, the US\$ was weaker against the EUR \((- 1.2\%)\) , but stronger against the CAD \((- 0.2\%)\) , and the GBP \((- 0.6\%)\) .

On a TTM basis, the Aftermarket index has underperformed the S&P 500 at \(+13.4\%\) through the end of July vs \(+14.8\%\) . YTD through the end of July, the Aftermarket Index has outperformed, posting a \(12.2\%\) increase vs the \(+7.8\%\) gain for the S&P 500. The industry avg P/E of 22.9x out- year earnings compares with 22.3x for the S&P 500 and the 20.4x 5- yr avg.

July brings record- setting temperatures in the Southeast, while precipitation levels are mixed throughout the country. In July the U.S. experienced temperatures above the LT average, and above July '24 averages. Most of the eastern US experienced hotter temperatures, with the Northeast recording the 4th hottest and the Southeast recording the hottest July in history, which we believe is likely to serve as a tailwind to demand for temperature control and cooling components. Precipitation levels were mixed throughout the country with the East North Central experiencing the 6th wettest July in history, while the Northeast, Southeast, West and Southwest all experienced drier than average climates in July. We continue to believe that the hot, dry weather should be supportive of increasing VMT as travel becomes more likely in "nicer" weather, especially in the summer months when many consumers tend to plan vacation, which, in turn, should boost the aftermarket through increased demand for vehicle maintenance and repair parts.
Figure 1 - Reported VMT (B's) vs. Jefferies VMT Prediction
Source: Jefferies, U.S. Dept. of Transportation

We use an additive regression- based BS TS (Bayesian Structural Time Series) to break down seasonality, trend, feature impacts, and noise terms in our VMT time series. The model is trained on VMT and collision data since 2013; the prediction is based on isolated seasonality terms and features derived from up- to- date collision data.

We update our predictive VMT model, projecting July driving volumes. This month, we update our proprietary predictive VMT model, capable of projecting July miles driven well in advance of available government data, which lags significantly ( \(\sim 1 - 2\) months). Our predictive model produces a strong correlation of projected miles driven vs reported values at \(\sim 88\%\) . Furthermore, our historical average prediction error is just \(\sim 2.8\%\) . Our model predicts that July VMT was 291.2B miles (+0.1% y/y), with an upper limit of 304.3B miles and a lower limit of 277.1B miles. In our view, our predictive VMT model provides a significantly more timely read-through to driving trends and the potential Aftermarket implications.
Figure 2 - Reported VMT (B's) vs. Jefferies VMT Prediction
Source: Jefferies,U.S.Dept.of Transportation

Miles Driven and Fuel Prices. June's miles driven (most recent available data) increased \(+0.9\%\) yr/yr to 285.6B miles, while recently released May VMT was \(+0.5\%\) yr/yr to 293.8B miles, as TTM miles driven increased \(+1.0\%\) yr/yr to 3.291T miles. Vehicle utilization saw encouraging continued growth in '24 with y/y expansion trending +LSD%, signaling a positive read-through for continued growth into '25. Fuel prices saw a continued y/y moderation, with national regular average fuel prices decreasing \(- 10.3\%\) yr/yr to \(\) 3.13\(per gallon, down 0.8\%\) from June.
Figure 3 - Monthly Miles Driven (Bs) and Fuel Prices
Source: Jefferies AAftermarket Team, Dept. of Transportation, Dept. of Transportatior, Dept. of Energy
Figure 4 - Trailing 12-Month Miles Driven (Bs)
Source: Jefferies Auto Aftermarket Team, Dept. of Transportation, Dept. of Transportation
Figure 5 - Miles Driven 2005-Current
Source:Jefferies Auto Aftermarket Team,Dept.of Transportation

Job creation falls well below expectations in July with downward revisions to May and June, while the unemployment rate ticks up slightly. As roughly one- third of miles driven are estimated to be employment- related (commuting and for work- related purposes), we see a continuation of COVID- related WFH marginally limiting vehicle travel in '25 vs pre- pandemic, but we view the current state of the US job market positively, despite concerns about a slowdown. We note that the seasonally adjusted unemployment rate increased 10 bps m/m in July to \(4.2\%\) , while seasonally adjusted nonfarm payrolls increased by \(+73K\) (vs expected \(+115K\) ) compared with the revised gain of \(+14K\) (vs initial \(+147K\) ) in June.
Figure 6 - Unemployment Rate, Seasonally Adjusted
Source:Jefferies,US Department of Labor,FactSet
Figure 7 - Nonfarm Payrolls, Seasonally Adjusted
Source:Jefferies,US Department of Labor,FactSet
Figure 8 - Miles Driven Breakout - 2022
Source: Jefferies, NHTs

Regional Miles Driven. June regional travel data (the most recent available) showed an increase in y/y vehicle utilization trends, with the Southwest and the Northwest both (+1.6% y/y) showing the largest increase, while the Northeast (- 0.3%) saw the only decrease.
Regional Miles Driven
Source: Jefferies, Dept of Transportation

The Southeast and Central regions had the largest volumes of vehicle miles driven in 2024, with 22% and 17% of the total, respectively. Moreover, according to total vehicle registrations by region in 2022 (the latest available data), the Southeast accounted for 20% of all registrations, while the Central and Northeast regions comprised the second- and third- largest regions at 16% and 15%, respectively.

Jefferies Tire Input Cost Index. Jefferies' quarterly tire input cost index decreased \(4.8\%\) y/y to 222.2 through the first month of Q3'25, representing a \(+0.2\%\) decrease from the prior quarter. Going forward, we expect tire input costs to moderate following inflation in recent years largely driven by elevated crude price. We note that increases in tire input costs could pressure tire manufacturers' margins, as nearly half of manufacturers' COGS are from these commodity inputs, while similarly weighing on consumer demand, potentially leading to replacement deferrals.
Figure 12 - Jefferies Tire Input Cost Index
Source: Jefferies, Dept. of Energy, Bureau of Labor Statistics

Collision - Scrap. Our Scrap Index, composed as an average aggregate of all five geographical zones from American Recycler News, decreased - 8.4% yr/yr to 204 in August, - 0.8% from the prior month. Salvage auction operators (CPRT and IAA) have headwinds from decreases in scrap pricing, as roughly 20% of transaction values are tied to underlying commodity pricing.
Figure 13 - Monthly Scrap Price Index
Source: Jefferies, American Recycler News

Used- Vehicle Values. We track various indices to measure changes in used vehicle values: the Manheim Used Vehicle Value Index (Manheim Index), the Black Book Wholesale Used Vehicle Retention Index (Black Book Index), the J.D. Power Index, and the Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers for used cars and trucks (CPI Used Vehicle Index).

In July, the Manheim Index increased \(+2.9\%\) y/y to 207.4, - 0.5% from the prior month. While the Manheim Index reflects changes in wholesale used vehicle values, it does not account for higher vehicle selling prices, due to improvements in vehicle quality over time. Therefore, we expect the Manheim Index to naturally trend upward as a growing mix of higher- quality, off- lease vehicles drives higher prices.

The J.D. Power Index was up \(15.7\%\) y/y to 239.1 in July, \(+0.8\%\) from the prior month. In our view, the J.D. Power Index is representative of the current used vehicle pricing market, as it provides a more apples- to- apples vehicle pricing comparison due to adjustments for improvements in vehicle quality.

The Black Book Index increased \(1.0\%\) y/y to 146.5 in July, but was down \(1.1\%\) from the prior month. The Black Book Index measures the average wholesale selling price of a vehicle relative to its "original typically equipped" MSRP.
The CPI Used Vehicle Index increased \(4.8\%\) y/y to 183.4 in July, \(+0.5\%\) from the prior month.

We believe that after significant increases in '21- '22 due to the pandemic and geopolitical OEM supply disruptions slowing new vehicle production, used vehicle values are likely to show signs of stabilization in '25, given potential price increases driven by auto tariffs and supply cadence improvements in '24. Higher unit valuations have supported both whole car auction RPU and dealer unit profits, while salvage auction operators have seen support from elevated ASPs as insurers write off higher- value vehicles while "run and drive" cars saw strong global demand.
Figure 14 - Used Vehicle Value Indices
Source: Jefferies, Manheim, NADA, Black Book, FRED

Warm weather has continued across the country, as we estimate that, in July, \(\sim 16\%\) of the store bases of AAP, AZO, GPC, and ORLY experienced higher temperatures than in \(85\%\) of prior Julys since '07. Meanwhile, \(\sim 18\%\) of their store bases saw more precipitation, with none of their store bases seeing more snowfall than in \(85\%\) of prior Julys since '07.

FX. During July, the average trade- weighted US\$ index was down \(4.9\%\) yr/yr and \(- 0.3\%\) sequentially. On a yr/yr basis, the US\$ was weaker against the CAD (- 0.1%), the EUR (- 7.1%) and the GBP (- 4.7%). Compared with the prior month, the US\$ was weaker against the EUR (- 1.2%), but stronger against the CAD (+0.2%), and the GBP (+0.6%).

Industry Performance. On a trailing- 12- month basis through the end of July, the Auto Aftermarket Index has underperformed the S&P 500, posting a \(13.4\%\) increase compared to a \(14.8\%\) increase for the S&P 500. The Automotive Aftermarket Index has outperformed YTD through July, posting a \(12.2\%\) increase compared to a \(7.8\%\) increase for the S&P 500.
Figure 27 - Year-to-Date Performance
Source:Jefferies,FactSet
Figure 28 - Trailing 12-month Performance
Source:Jefferies,FactSet

Valuation. The current industry average P/E of 22.9x out- year earnings compares with 22.3x for the S&P 500 and the five- year industry average of 20.4x. Valuations have increased in 2025, as the industry average P/E was 22.0x at 2024 year- end.

series.values: The image displays a scatter plot of numerous red dots overlaid on a map of the United States, indicating the geographical distribution of these points. Due to the nature of the image (a map with many small, indistinguishable points), it is not feasible to extract individual coordinate values for each point. The points are concentrated more heavily in the eastern half of the US and along the west coast, with sparser distribution in the central and mountain west regions.
